04300nam a22005535i 9781503619128DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036191287 a10.1515/97815036191282doi  a(DE-B1597)581593  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0090002bisacsh00aWhat’s Left of Enlightenment? :bA Postmodern Question /ced. by Keith M. Baker, Peter Hanns Reill. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has become increasingly clear in recent years that, for all their differences, the many varieties of thinking commonly grouped together under the rubric of “postmodernism” share at least one salient characteristic: they all depend upon a stereotyped account of the Enlightenment. Postmodernity requires a “modernity” to be repudiated and superseded, and the tenets of this modernity have invariably been identified with the so-called Enlightenment Project. This volume aims to explore critically the now conventional opposition between Enlightenment and Postmodernity and question some of the conclusions drawn from it. In so doing, the authors focus on three general areas. Part I, “Enlightenment or Postmodernity?”, reflects on the way in which contemporary discussion characterizes the two movements as radical alternatives. Part II, “Critical Confrontations,” provides a kind of archaeology of this opposition by charting a series of critical engagements by those who have affirmed or demeaned Enlightenment values in the twentieth century. Part III, “A Postmodern Enlightenment?”, complicates the perceived dichotomy between Enlightenment and Postmodernity by pointing to the existence within the Enlightenment of elements frequently seen as characteristic of Postmodernity. The contributors are Lorraine Daston, Dena Goodman, David Hollinger, Lawrence E. Klein, Jonathan Knudsen, Michael Meranze, Richard Rorty, Hans Sluga, and Johnson Kent Wright.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Keith M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDaston, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Dena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollinger, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Lawrence E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnudsen, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeranze, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReill, Peter Hanns, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRorty, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSluga, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWright, Johnson Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361912840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619128/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles